The Constituent Assembly (CA) immediately after the promulgation of the Interim Constitution of Nepal in 2007 till the end of 2009 spent around six months in number of sessions discussing and debating the Constitution writing draft. However, it could not reach to consensus due to sharp political divide along ethnic, regional parties’ lines. The aptitude of political parties coming to the consensus remained elusive, and they were unable to avoid the ethnic federalism issue. The expulsion of Nepali Congress (NC) from inter-party mechanism, or commonly known as IPRAMC, is welcomed by leftist alliance but democrats have expressed their skepticism about its relevance. The NC was expelled from the IPRAMC on Friday on charges that it refused to share the power during interim period.Two years ago, then prime minister K. P. Sharma Oli and a NC leader Madhav Kumar Nepal had reached an accord saying that the former may not extend the tenure of House of Representatives and would dissolve it without any schedule. Such a rule would have helped both. The NC had accepted this proposal was meant for a short period of time.
